		<b>Comment By John Clayton, 12-11-07</b>
		<p>Thanks for the endorsement, Jenny! <br />
<br />
There was also great fiction set in Wyoming this year. One of my favorites was Alyson Hagy's novel "Snow, Ashes."</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Jenny Shank, 12-11-07</b>
		<p>"Snow, Ashes" was a book I meant to get to this year but hadn't yet...so many books, so little time.  Thanks for mentioning it.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Jeff Lee, 12-13-07</b>
		<p>Jenny,<br />
<br />
  What a great and thoughtful list -- both Part I & II! Thanks for highlighting so many good books, and especially ones that don't always get the attention they deserve. You've kept me up-to-date all year long. I don't know of a better book source out there!<br />
<br />
  You mentioned Utah's quiet year for books. There's two really interesting titles coming up next year from Utah writers, both non-fiction:<br />
<br />
--Trespass: Living at the Edge of the Promised Land, by Amy Irvine, a memoir about growing up Mormon, and living the life of a wilderness advocate in southern Utah.<br />
<br />
--Bargaining for Eden: The Fight for the Last Open Spaces in America: by Stephen Trimble, one of the West's best author/photographer who lives in SLC.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Stephen Trimble, 12-20-07</b>
		<p>Jenny:<br />
<br />
And my thanks to Jeff for his enthusiasm for my upcoming book.<br />
<br />
My favorite Utah book this year covers more ground than just Utah, but it's a gem.  Renny Russell's  "Rock Me on the Water: A Life on the Loose" is a wonderful read for any of us who came of age as environmentalists around the time of the first Earth Day in 1970.  Renny and his brother Terry published "On the Loose" in 1967, and a lot of us love it dearly as a celebratory introduction to wilderness.  The book also told of Terry Russell's loss in a rapid on the Green River.  Now here comes Renny, forty years later, telling the stories of life without his brother and of his adventures in Glen Canyon and the Escalante from the perspective of a middle-aged man looking back.  The new book completes the story of the original in a most moving way.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Amable, 12-20-07</b>
		<p>One more you should get and review, Jenny  Two issues---immigrantion and water in the West---are infused brilliantly but without all the political overtones in a new novel from TCU Press this year by seasoned and award winning pro, Bob Cherry, native Texan living in Wyoming.  Moving Serafina takes the reader on a powerful and heart wrenching journey into the lives of unique characters along the Texas/Mexico border as only Cherry can.   I think he's one the most gifted writers of the contemporary West.  Check it out!<br />
<a href="http://www.newwest.net/?URL=http%3A%2F%2Fbobcherry.com">http://bobcherry.com</a></p>
		
